choi, chan, stuecker, chun, newcombe, and venkateswaran: a fosmid clonin stratey for detectin the widest possible spectrum of microbes from the international space station drinkin water system



oriinal article 


enomics & informatics 2012; 10(4): 249-255.

published online: december 31, 2012 
doi: https://doi.or/10.5808/i.2012.10.4.249




a fosmid clonin stratey for detectin the widest possible spectrum of microbes from the international space station drinkin water system

sandun choi 1, 2*, mi sook chan 2, tara stuecker 3, christine chun 2, david a. newcombe 3, kasthuri venkateswaran 3**


1department of molecular science and technoloy, ajou university, suwon 443-749, korea.
2division of bioloy, california institute of technoloy, pasadena, ca 91125, usa.
3jet propulsion laboratory, california institute of technoloy, pasadena, ca 91109, usa.



*correspondin author 1: tel: +82-31-219-2600, fax: +82-31-219-1615, sandunchoi@ajou.ac.kr
 

**correspondin author 2: tel: +1-818-393-1481, fax: +1-818-393-4176, kjvenkat@jpl.nasa.ov
 

 received october 06, 2012       revised october 28, 2012       accepted november 05, 2012

copyriht © 2012 by the korea enome oranization 
 (open-access, http://creativecommons.or/licenses/by-nc/3.0/):  
it is identical to the creative commons attribution non-commercial license (http://creativecommons.or/licenses/by-nc/3.0/).




abstract

in this study, fosmid clonin strateies were used to assess the microbial populations in water from the international space station (iss) drinkin water system (henceforth referred to as prebiocide and tank a water samples). the oals of this study were: to compare the sensitivity of the fosmid clonin stratey with that of traditional culture-based and 16s rrna-based approaches and to detect the widest possible spectrum of microbial populations durin the water purification process. initially, microbes could not be cultivated, and conventional pcr failed to amplify 16s rdna framents from these low biomass samples. therefore, randomly primed rollin-circle amplification was used to amplify any dna that miht be present in the samples, followed by size selection by usin pulsed-field el electrophoresis. the amplified hih-molecular-weiht dna from both samples was cloned into fosmid vectors. several hundred clones were randomly selected for sequencin, followed by blastn/blastx searches. sequences encodin specific enes from burkholderia, a species abundant in the soil and roundwater, were found in both samples. bradyrhizobium and mesorhizobium, which belon to rhizobia, a lare community of nitroen fixers often found in association with plant roots, were present in the prebiocide samples. ralstonia, which is prevalent in soils with a hih heavy metal content, was detected in the tank a samples. the detection of many unidentified sequences suests the presence of potentially novel microbial finerprints. the bacterial diversity detected in this pilot study usin a fosmid vector approach was hiher than that detected by conventional 16s rrna ene sequencin.
keywords: fosmid, international space station, multiple displacement amplification, rollin-circle amplification 





introduction
rationin and water recyclin are an essential part of life at international space stations (isss) [1]. water purification machines on the iss partly mimic these processes, but they do not rely on microbes or any other livin oranisms. these machines cleanse wastewater in a 3-step process. the first step involves a filter that removes particles and debris. the water then passes throuh multifiltration beds that contain substances that remove oranic and inoranic impurities. finally, the catalytic oxidation reactor removes volatile oranic compounds and kills bacteria and viruses. once the water is purified, astronauts try to ensure that the water is used with maximum possible efficiency. even with intense conservation and recyclin efforts, the space station will radually lose water because of inefficiencies in the life support system.
water that passes throuh animals' bodies is refreshed by natural processes [2]. microbes in the soil break down urea and convert it to a form that plants can absorb and use to build new plant tissue. water excreted by animals also evaporates into the atmosphere and rains back down to the earth as freshwater-a natural form of distillation. isss always need to be resupplied with water, because no water reprocessin technoloy is currently available for use in space. national aeronautics and space administration (nasa) scientists continue to look for ways to improve the life-support systems of space stations, which can thereby reduce water losses and aid in findin ways to reuse other waste products. bacteria and viruses are extraordinarily abundant in water, soil, and sediment microbial ecosystems [3]. in drinkin water, soil, and sediment, viral abundance exceeds that of co-existin host populations by 10- to 100-fold [4]. microscopy and molecular enetic tools have been critical in demonstratin that bacteria and viruses are dynamic components of microbial ecosystems capable of sinificantly influencin the productivity and population bioloy of their host communities. moreover, these approaches have beun to describe the immense enetic diversity of viral communities. a critical first step in the application of many cultivation-independent approaches to virus ecoloy is obtainin a viral concentrate from an environmental sample. culture-dependent methods also rely on viruses bein present at sufficiently hih levels to be detected [3]. in this study, the methodoloy for the isolation and concentration of viruses from water, soil, and aquatic sediment samples has been discussed in detail.
microoranisms constitute two-thirds of the earth's bioloical diversity [5, 6]. as many as 99% of the microbes present in certain environments can not be detected by reular techniques [7]. protocols have been developed to assess unexplored microbial diversity in order to overcome the existin barriers that prevent the estimation of biodiversity [8]. new screenin methods have been desined to construct specific fosmid libraries that can help distinuish novel microbial populations in drinkin water samples [9]. to screen the complete populations, clonin vectors, like fosmids and bacterial artificial chromosomes (bacs), are bein developed [10-12]. this article describes the various methodoloies and tools that have been developed to understand and identify the widest spectrum of microbial communities, includin bacteria, archaea, and viruses, throuh fosmid clonin analysis.
bacteriophae phi29 (φ29) dna polymerase, the 66-kd product of viral ene 2, has been shown to be capable of efficient dna amplification both in vitro and in vivo [13-15]. this enzyme is very reliable with respect to the amplification of enomic dna for constructin libraries, especially when the startin enomic material is limited. this enzyme requires 2 proteins for its activity: viral dna polymerase p2 and φ29 terminal protein p3 [16]. the enzyme has hih processivity (>70 kb) and a remarkable strand-displacement ability with sinle-stranded dna and double-stranded dna. based on this enzymatic characteristic, the replication of both dna strands can be processed from each terminal-primin event without the synthesis of rna-primed okazaki framents. the enzyme also has a 3'-5' proofreadin exonuclease function [17].
bacteriophae ϕdna polymerase amplifies circular dna in a rollin-circle amplification (rca) mechanism. this characteristic has been used to amplify and clone the complete circular dna enome of bacteria and viruses. the amplified dna could be used for direct sequencin and was cloned after diestion with a sinle cuttin restriction endonuclease. the use of this enzyme simplified the clonin steps and increased the clonin efficiency of the complete enome of circular dna viruses [18]. the φ29 dna polymerase was ideal for our project because of the limited amount of startin material available. in addition, the microbes in our sample could not be cultivated usin traditional approaches. usin exonuclease-resistant random primers, dean and colleaues have achieved up to a 10,000-fold amplification from 1 n of m13 template and have also improved the averae product lenth to reater than 40 kb [19]. the method is based on multiple displacement amplification technoloy and provides hih yields of approximately 40 µ of dna from only a few enome copies.
in a previous study on subsurface flow-constructed wetlands, pcr-based methods were developed and used for the detection of pathoenic microbial populations, such as campylobacter spp. and yersinia enterocolitica, in treated wastewater [20, 21]. in this study, we constructed fosmid libraries to assess the microbial diversity in drinkin roundwater samples from kennedy space center's round service equipment tank and the space shuttle water tank (iodine-treated water) and examined the samples for the presence of many different bacterial populations durin the water purification processes. the oals of this study were: 1) to compare the sensitivity of the fosmid clonin stratey with that of traditional culture-based and 16s rrna-based approaches and 2) to detect the widest possible spectrum of microbial populations durin the water purification process.


methods

 collection of water samples
two drinkin water samples from the kennedy space center, orlando, florida, usa-namely, water samples from the round service equipment tank (prebiocide) and the space shuttle water tank (iodine-treated water; tank a)-were collected for microbial diversity assessment.


 isolation of enomic dna
approximately 500 ml each of the prebiocide and tank a water samples was concentrated usin several amicon ultra-15 filters (50k nmwl; millipore, billerica, ma, usa). the filtered concentrates were combined toether and further concentrated to 100 µl by usin a vacuum evaporator (ht-4 ii evaporation system; enevac inc., valley cottae, ny, usa) at 28℃ for 2 h. dna isolation was conducted usin trizol reaent, followin the instructions provided by the manufacturer (invitroen, carlsbad, ca, usa). durin the last step, the dna pellets were dissolved in 10 µl of 8 mm naoh and then incubated at 60℃ for 10 min.


 amplification of enomic dna
the purified dna was subjected to randomly primed rca to amplify any dna present in the water samples, accordin to the procedure detailed in the enomiphi dna amplification kit manual (amersham biosciences, piscataway, nj, usa). this kit consists of 3 components: the sample buffer; the reaction buffer; and an enzyme mix containin random primers, dntps, and φ29 dna polymerase [22]. one microliter of the concentrated water sample from either the prebiocide or tank a was denatured with 9 µl of sample buffer at 95℃ for 5 min and cooled rapidly on ice. the amplification reaction was performed by addin 9 µl of reaction buffer and 1 µl of enzyme mix to the denatured sample. the reaction mixtures were incubated at 30℃ for 16 h. after amplification, the tubes were incubated at 65℃ for 10 min to inactivate the φ29 dna polymerase enzyme. the amplified enomic dna was precipitated by ethanol and then dissolved in 10 mm tris-hcl (ph 7.5) and 1 mm ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid. most of the random primers and dntps were removed after precipitation with ethanol.


 construction of the fosmid library
the amplified hih-molecular-weiht dna from the prebiocide or tank a water samples was cloned with fosmid vectors. in order to select dna framents loner than 20 kb, the amplified dna was visualized by pulsed-field el electrophoresis (pfe) in 1% low-meltin-point aarose at 4.5 v/cm in 1 × tbe buffer for 13 h. dna framents larer than 20 kb were cut out, extracted from the el, and re-run for 5 h under the same conditions. these resolved dna framents were used to construct a fosmid library by followin the procedure detailed by the manufacturer. usin the copycontrol fosmid library construction kit (epicentre, madison, wi, usa), the sheared dna was end-repaired to enerate blunt 5'-phosphorylated ends and then liated directly into the clonin-ready copycontrol pcc1fos vector (fi. 1) at a 10:1 vector:insert ratio. the liated dna was then packaed usin ultrahih-efficiency maxplax lambda packain extract (epicentre) and was plated on phae t1-resistant escherichia coli cells to produce the library. packain a sinle 10-µl liation reaction enerated more than 100,000 fosmid clones from the dna isolated from the prebiocide and tank a water samples. dna from several randomly chosen clones was purified usin the direct lysis fosmid96 kit (epicentre) for hih-throuhput fosmid sequencin.


 restriction enzyme analysis
one microliter of the rca product from the prebiocide or the tank a samples was incubated with 10 u of hindiii at 37℃ overniht. restriction diestion products were separated by 1% aarose el electrophoresis and visualized by ethidium bromide stainin. in addition, amon the 9,740 clones obtained from the fosmid library constructs, subsets of randomly selected clones from the prebiocide or tank a samples were diested with noti restriction enzyme for measurin insert dna sizes.


 dna sequencin
each colony from the different libraries was picked and then inoculated in luria broth media containin chloramphenicol and lycerol (10%, final concentration) in a 384-well plate. the cells were cultured at 37℃ for 1 day and stored at -80℃. dna was isolated usin the qiaen miniprep kit (qiaen, valencia, ca, usa) accordin to the manufacturer's instructions. initially, 100 clones from each library were selected for the sequencin reaction (macroen, seoul, korea). blast sequence homoloy searches were conducted aainst the enbank database after subtractin the vector sequence. subsequently, 1,260 colonies from the prebiocide library and 2,600 colonies from the tank a library were sequenced. the major sequences encodin specific enes were identified from both prebiocide and tank a samples on the basis of protein sequences (with more than 75 amino acid residues) from enbank.


 pcr detection of different microbial roups in drinkin water samples
dna was extracted from the prebiocide and tank a water samples by usin the qiaen miniprep kit. several microbial roups were analyzed by pcr amplification of ene framents of several phyloenetic roups representin different microbial communities [23]. these roups included eneral bacteria, bacillus species, ram-positive bacteria (hih  + c content), streptomyces species, eukaryotes (funi, protists, and reen alae), and eneral funi. the pcr primer pairs used in the analysis and the roups they represent are listed in table 1.



results

 enomic dna amplification usin the phi29 dna polymerase
the dna plu did not show any detectable amount of dna when analyzed usin pfe. the enomiphi dna amplification kit (amersham biosciences) is claimed to have very hih sensitivity for dna detection; the smallest trace of dna should be amplified if present. in the protocol provided with the amplification kit, it is recommended that the amplification reaction be started with 10 n of dna. althouh the results initially showed that the concentrated samples did not contain any detectable amount of dna, the amplification procedure was continued with these samples. the control (dnase free water) and the dna isolated from the prebiocide and tank a samples showed a similarly positive pattern after dna amplification, which seemed to be nonspecific due to the contamination of the φ29 dna polymerase enzyme with exoenous dna (fi. 2a). similarly, the positive controls, such as lambda dna, showed sinificant amplification of up to 20-30 µ in a 20-µl reaction. the distribution of the amplified dna raned from 20 to 40 kb. repeated trials of less than 3 h did not result in any amplification; however, a dna product was noted after 6 h of incubation. the size of the amplified dna (between 20 kb and 40 kb) was determined by pfe.
the enomiphi dna amplification kit manual explains that nonspecific amplification usually occurs, even in the absence of template dna, because of the presence of random primers and the hih amplification performance capability of the enzyme. in order to confirm whether the amplified dna had been specifically amplified from the enomic dna template, 1 µ of each of the amplified dna samples was diested with hindiii (fi. 2b). several framented dna bands with expected sizes were observed in the diestion reaction of the amplified dna from the lambda (positive control), prebiocide, tank a, and control samples, showin that the amplification was specific. smeared bands of indiestible dna were also obtained because of partial and/or nonspecific amplification of the enomic dna.


 construction of fosmid vector libraries
before constructin the fosmid vector libraries, several domain or species-specific pcr reactions were performed. both the prebiocide and tank a samples and the control (dnase-free water) showed amplification with different primer sets (fi. 3). primer pairs used for species-specific pcr amplification to detect the microbial diversity are listed in table 1 [24-26]. after constructin the fosmid vector libraries, 4,000 clones from the prebiocide sample, 2,290 clones from the tank a sample, and 3,450 clones from the control were picked. as expected, noti diestion of the fosmid dna released and produced inserts that were more than 40 kb in size (fi. 4). subsets diested with the noti enzyme were sequenced. only dna sequences that exhibited more than 80% similarity with an existin enbank sequence were included in the analysis.


 dna sequence analysis
blast sequence homoloy searches were also performed aainst the enbank database after subtractin the vector sequence. subsequently, 1,260 sinle colonies from the prebiocide library and 2,600 sinle colonies from the tank a library were picked. the major sequences encodin specific enes were then identified from the prebiocide (26 clones), tank a (27 clones), and control samples (21 clones) on the basis of the enbank protein sequences. supplementary table 1 shows representative blast search results from enbank for the prebiocide, tank a, and control sample clones.


 identification of microbial populations and diversity
the microbial populations, identified on the basis of sequences for both the prebiocide and tank a drinkin water samples, are listed in table 2 and supplementary table 1. bradyrhizobium japonicum, mesorhizobium loti, and bradyrhizobium species were present in the prebiocide library. bradyrhizobium and mesorhizobium belon to rhizobia, a lare community of nitroen fixers often found in association with plant roots [27]. ralstonia metallidurans and r. eutropha were detected in tank a. strains of r. metallidurans (renamed as cupriavidus metallidurans strain ch34) are prevalent in soils with hih heavy metal content [28]. sequences encodin specific enes from burkholderia funorum, a species abundant in soil and roundwater, were found in both the prebiocide and tank a samples [23, 29]. protein sequences homoloous to those of several enera of opportunistic pathoens were retrieved by rca. the enomic dna amplification by pcr detected different microbial roups in drinkin water samples (table 1, fi. 3).



discussion
in the current study, a fosmid clonin stratey was used to assess the microbial populations in the iss drinkin water system-namely, samples from the prebiocide and tank a. initially, no microbes could be cultivated, and conventional pcr reactions failed to amplify 16s rdna framents from low biomass samples. therefore, randomly primed rca was used to amplify any dna present in the samples, followed by size selection usin pfe. enomic dna amplification was performed usin the dna isolated from concentrated dna samples obtained from prebiocide and tank a drinkin water samples in the iss.
we used the enomiphi dna amplification kit from amersham; the dna amplification experiments usin a φ29 dna polymerase proved to be ideal for the scarce amount of enomic startin material available. however, nonspecific amplification can occur either in the presence or in the absence of the dna template in the reaction. for the lambda dna sample, the presence of amplified dna can be confirmed if the φ29 dna polymerase is specific to the template dna by diestion with restriction enzymes. lambda dna (48.5 kb) has many hindiii restriction sites, producin a unique distribution of sizes. however, even in the case of lambda dna, we confirmed that some amount of indiestible amplified dna still exists, which appears to be due to nonspecific amplification and/or partial amplification (fi. 2b). accordin to the amersham kit user manual, the enzyme synthesizes sinle-stranded dna or double-stranded dna. an alternative explanation is that there were many sinle-stranded dna framents that could not be cut by restriction enzymes. to test this theory, the amplified dna was denatured at 95℃ for 3 min and reannealed at room temperature for 30 min to decrease the amount of sinle-stranded dna. however, restriction diestion still resulted in a lare amount of indiestible dna (data not shown).
usin the concentrated water samples also proved that such samples had sufficient dna, which could be used to amplify enomic dna by usin commercially available kits, even when only a few microbes were present. nevertheless, amplification of enomic dna may require some additional dna preparation steps, because boilin cells for a short time may not effectively release the enomic dna for use as template. we decreased the incidence of nonspecific amplification by reducin the incubation time to less than 12 h when it was possible to use the amplified dna as a template.
the amplified hih-molecular-weiht dna obtained from the prebiocide, tank a, and control samples was cloned into fosmid vectors. several hundred clones were randomly selected for sequencin, which was followed by blastn/blastx searches (table 2, supplementary table 1). sequences encodin specific enes from burkholderia, a species abundant in soil and roundwater, were obtained for both the prebiocide and tank a samples [23, 29]. bradyrhizobium and mesorhizobium, belonin to rhizobia, a lare community of nitroen fixers often found in association with plant roots, were present in the prebiocide library [27]. ralstonia, which is prevalent in soils with a hih heavy metal content, was detected in the tank a library [28]. iardia lamblia is a common cause of diarrhea in humans, and the presence of homoloous protein sequences with the protein encoded by . lamblia in tank a samples warrants further study [30].
the current nasa technoloies used for treatin drinkin water in the iss are effective in removin viable cultivable microbes. conventional pcr failed to detect any amplifiable rrna enes, which suests that the purification of this drinkin water was satisfactory. however, the amplification of naked dna from these samples enabled elucidation of the microbial diversity in the samples. when drinkin water was not treated with a biocide, protein sequences from diverse enera could be retrieved. the detection of many unidentified sequences (data not shown) also suests the presence of potentially novel microbial finerprints. the bacterial diversity observed in this pilot study with the fosmid approach was reater than that observed with conventional 16s rrna ene sequencin.

04. Converting Text to Numbers¶

In [66]:
type(word)
new_word = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z\s]", "",raw)
NW = list(new_word)
numList = []
for i in range(len(NW)):
    numList.append(ord(NW[i]))
    
# 텍스트 문자열 문자 하나씩 아스키코드로 변환.    
numList
# 텍스트 문자열 숫자로 변환 후 한 줄에 출력.
print(*numList)
